1. Introduction¶

Currently, gas filtration via porous membranes is used as a technological alternative to conventional separation processes such as distillation, absorption, extraction. Gas and vapor transportation through porous materials is affected by various factors. Gas transmission for microporous membranes is closely related to porosity, membrane thickness, and mean pore size. Molar flow intensity (Molar flux) is defined as the quantity of a given mole of gas passing through a unit surface area in unit time and expressed in [mol.m−2.s−1][mol.m−2.s−1]. In membrane science, it is most common to associate performance with two properties, permeability and selectivity. Permeance is the ratio of gas molar flux to the pressure difference on two sides of membrane. Permeance is expressed as [mol.m−2.s−1Pa−1][mol.m−2.s−1Pa−1]. The selectivity is definded as a ratio betwwen the permeances of two corresponding gas. Selectivity is the unitless physical quantity

Permeation of gases in membrane system is a complicated phenomena. In general, transport flux can be either diffusion flow or viscous flow. Convective flow occurs in porous membranes, while diffusion occurs in dense or non-porous membranes. Convective (non-diffusive) flow can generally be categorized into three different mechanisms: Poiseuille (Viscous) flow, Knudsen flow and Surface flow.

In most porous membranes, convective flow of mass or heat much more important than diffusive flow. Mechanisms of flow of gas molecules through pores and dense membranes are shown in figure below. In some cases, depending on the properties of the gas as well as the membrane material, two or more gas transport mechanisms can occur simultaneously.

Figure 1.1 Gas transport mechanisms (a) Viscous flow, (b) Knudsen flow, (c) solution-diffusion

2. Laboratory Procedure¶

The apparatus of experiment is ilustrated in the figure below. It includes 3 pressure vessels containing different gas connect to a porous membrane module. The internal pressure of apparatus was measured by indicator p1, the outlet pressure was measured by indicator p2, and the differential pressure indicator was used to measure the pressure drop through membrane.

Figure 2.1 Scheme of experiment apparatus

The procedure below is followed to conduct the experiment:

  • Step 1: Cleaning Open Valves: V1, V2, V4, V5 and V8 (slightly for very short time),Closed Valves: V3, V6, V7 The first step to clean the system from previous experiment residuals (in our case N2). For this reason, we must set the system to H2 and open the valve 8. For simplicity I refer to V as valve in the following text. Since there is a huge pressure (about 20 bar) behind V8, we must keep the valve of at least 1 reservoir open to avoid a possible damage to the system and module, before opening V8. For cleaning the system, we open V1, V2, V4 and V5 and then open V8 slightly and smoothly for a very short time and then close again. In fact, we do not open the V8 completely, we just play with it. Due to the high pressure, system will be filled in milliseconds.

  • Step 2: Filling Open Valves: V1, V2, Closed Valves: V3, V4, V5, V6, V7 and V8 After doing the previous step for few times, now we are sure that our system is excluded from all the N2. Now we should let the reservoirs to be filled with H2. For this reason, we close V4 and V5 and we fill the reservoirs with H2. Our pressure reached a value about 900-950 KPa.

  • Step 3: Closing *Open Valves: None Closed Valves: All

  • Afterward, we close all the valves. Since our membrane is dense, we expect low permeability and flux. Thus, we need the smallest reservoir to be able to record the pressure drop during the experiment. For this reason, we use the volume inside the main tube (440 mL) of the system and close the reservoir’s valves.

  • Step 4: Stabilization Open Valves: V7 Closed Valves: All except V7 Afterward, we close all the valves. Since our membrane is dense, we expect low permeability and flux. Thus, we need the smallest reservoir to be able to record the pressure drop during the experiment. For this reason, we use the volume inside the main tube (440 mL) of the system and close the reservoir’s valves.

  • Step 5: Experiment Open Valves: V1,Closed Valves: All except V7 For the first experiment we closed the A2 outlet. After stabilization, we start to record the pressure drop data as a function of time. We continued the experiment as far as the pressure reached about 300 KPa. For our case, it took about 20-25 minutes. Then we stopped the recording.

3. Method¶

3.1 Derive a model of the gas transport mechanism in porous media

Cross membrane flux of i-th component can be written as follow:

Ji=ΠiδM×ΔpiJi=ΠiδM×Δpi

The total permeat flow rate can be written as, the negative sign is indicated that the flow rate will be decrease over time:

dnidt=−Am×Jidnidt=−Am×Ji

Consider ideal-gas state:

ni=piVRT→dnidt=VRT×dpidtni=piVRT→dnidt=VRT×dpidt

, so we have:

dpidt=−ARTV×Ji=Q×Jidpidt=−ARTV×Ji=Q×Ji

Because the dpidt=d(pi(t)−pa)dt=dΔpidtdpidt=d(pi(t)−pa)dt=dΔpidt, so

dΔpidt=−Q×Ji(1)dΔpidt=−Q×Ji(1)

The permeate flow rate calculation only consider the Knudsen diffusion and viscous flow. Therefore, the cross membrane flux can be written as the sum of two different flow component.

Ji=JKnudseni+JViscousiJi=JiKnudsen+JiViscous

Knudsen diffusion is a diffuision mechanism that occurs when the pore size is comparable to or smaller than the mean free path of the gas component. The Knudsen flow can be calculated by the below equation, which DK=2rϵ3RT8RTπM−−−−√DK=2rϵ3RT8RTπM.

JKnudseni=DKδMΔp=ΠKiΔpJiKnudsen=DKδMΔp=ΠiKΔp

Otherwise, Viscous flow occurs when the pore size is much bigger than the mean free path of the gas component. The Viscous flow can be calculated by the below equation, which is Dp=r2ϵ8ηRTDp=r2ϵ8ηRT.

JViscousi=Dp2δM(p2i−p2a)=ΠPi2(p2i−p2a)JiViscous=Dp2δM(pi2−pa2)=ΠiP2(pi2−pa2)

We also can see that:

p2i−p2a=(pi−pa)(pi+pa)=(pi−pa)(pi−pa+2pa)pi2−pa2=(pi−pa)(pi+pa)=(pi−pa)(pi−pa+2pa)

so

12(p2i−p2a)=12(Δp(Δp+2pa))=(Δp22+paΔp)12(pi2−pa2)=12(Δp(Δp+2pa))=(Δp22+paΔp)

The Viscous flow can be transformed as follow:

JViscousi=12ΠPiΔp2+paΠPiΔpJiViscous=12ΠiPΔp2+paΠiPΔp

The equation (1) can be written as:

dΔpidt=Q×Ji=Q×(JKnudseni+JViscousi)=Q×(ΠKiΔp+12ΠPiΔp2+paΠPiΔp)dΔpidt=Q×Ji=Q×(JiKnudsen+JiViscous)=Q×(ΠiKΔp+12ΠiPΔp2+paΠiPΔp)
Rearrange the above equation, we can obtaine:
dΔpi(paΠPi+ΠKi)Δp+12ΠPiΔp2=Q.dtdΔpi(paΠiP+ΠiK)Δp+12ΠiPΔp2=Q.dt

Intergrate both side, from Δp0Δp0 to ΔpΔp on the left hand side and 0 to t on the right hand side:

∫ΔpΔp0dΔpi(paΠPi+ΠKi)Δp+12ΠPiΔp2=Q.∫t0dt∫Δp0ΔpdΔpi(paΠiP+ΠiK)Δp+12ΠiPΔp2=Q.∫0tdt

To simplify the integral, we call K1=ΠP.pa+ΠKK1=ΠP.pa+ΠK and K2=12ΠPK2=12ΠP, we can obtain:

∫ΔpΔp0dΔpiK1Δp+K2Δp2=Q.∫t0dt(2)∫Δp0ΔpdΔpiK1Δp+K2Δp2=Q.∫0tdt(2)

The integration task will be carried by sympysympy, symbolic computation package of python.

3.2 Nonlinear curve fitting using Newton-Gaussian method

The concept of curve fitting is to find the parameter constant to minimize the residue. In this report, the magnitude of residue is estimated by Least-Square method. To perform the nonlinear regression using Gauss-Newton method, we write out equation for each measured sample.

y1=f(x1,a)+e1y2=f(x2,a)+e2⋮yn=f(xn,a)+eny1=f(x1,a)+e1y2=f(x2,a)+e2⋮yn=f(xn,a)+en

with a = [a0,a1,...,ai][a0,a1,...,ai] is the constant parameters We can convert the nonlinear equations into linear equations by expanding them into multi-parameter Taylor series.

y1=f(x1)+∂f(x1)∂a0Δa0+∂f(x1)∂a1Δa1+...∂f(x1)∂aiΔai+e1y2=f(x2)+∂f(x2)∂a0Δa0+∂f(x2)∂a1Δa1+...∂f(x2)∂aiΔai+e2⋮yn=f(xn)+∂f(xn)∂a0Δa0+∂f(xn)∂a1Δa1+...∂f(xn)∂aiΔai+eny1=f(x1)+∂f(x1)∂a0Δa0+∂f(x1)∂a1Δa1+...∂f(x1)∂aiΔai+e1y2=f(x2)+∂f(x2)∂a0Δa0+∂f(x2)∂a1Δa1+...∂f(x2)∂aiΔai+e2⋮yn=f(xn)+∂f(xn)∂a0Δa0+∂f(xn)∂a1Δa1+...∂f(xn)∂aiΔai+en

We can rewrite as matrix:

y=f(x)+J.Δa+Ey=f(x)+J.Δa+E

with matrix JJ is:

Jn×i=⎡⎣⎢⎢⎢⎢⎢⎢⎢⎢∂f(x1)∂a0∂f(x2)∂a0⋮∂f(xn)∂a0∂f(x1)∂a1∂f(x2)∂a1⋮∂f(xn)∂a1⋯⋯⋱⋯∂f(x1)∂ai∂f(x2)∂ai⋮∂f(xn)∂ai⎤⎦⎥⎥⎥⎥⎥⎥⎥⎥Jn×i=[∂f(x1)∂a0∂f(x1)∂a1⋯∂f(x1)∂ai∂f(x2)∂a0∂f(x2)∂a1⋯∂f(x2)∂ai⋮⋮⋱⋮∂f(xn)∂a0∂f(xn)∂a1⋯∂f(xn)∂ai]

We solve for ΔaΔa using least-squares. Assume E≈0E≈0, we have:

y=f(x)+J.Δa⟹y−f(x)=J.Δa⟹d=J.Δa(JT.J)Δa=JT.d⟹Δa=(JT.J)−1JT.dy=f(x)+J.Δa⟹y−f(x)=J.Δa⟹d=J.Δa(JT.J)Δa=JT.d⟹Δa=(JT.J)−1JT.d

Finally, we can update parameter aa for the next iteration. To ensure convergence of algorithm, we introduce some under relaxation factor ββ.

a⟵a+β.Δaa⟵a+β.Δa

To obtain the matrix JJ We need to derive analytical expresions for partial derivative of f(x)f(x). The task will be carried by sympysympy, symbolic computation package of python.

∂f(x)∂L,∂f(x)∂K,∂f(x)∂C∂f(x)∂L,∂f(x)∂K,∂f(x)∂C

4. Calculation and Result¶

4.1 Non-linear fitting¶

In [83]:
# --- fitting function
def fitting_func(L,K,C):
    return L*(np.exp(K*Q*t + C)/(1-np.exp(K*Q*t + C)))

# --- function for analytical differentiation

def dpdL(L,K,C):
    return fitting_func(L,K,C)/L

def dpdK(L,K,C):
    return Q*t*fitting_func(L,K,C) + Q*t/L*fitting_func(L,K,C)**2

def dpdC(L,K,C):
    return fitting_func(L,K,C) + 1/L*fitting_func(L,K,C)**2

T = 298.15          # Temperature [K]
R = 8.314           # Univeral gas constant [J/mol/K]
V = 0.544e-3        # Apparatus volume [m3]
A = 0.7274635e-4    # Membrane area (membrane type K) [m2]
eta= 11.042e-6      # Gas dymanic viscosity (CH4) [Pa.s]
Mw = 16e-3          # Molar mass (CH4) [kg/mol]
rp = 1e-7           # Mean pore radius estimate [m]
Q = -R*T*A/V;       # Q constant

In [145]:
# --- Intelligent Initial Guess
pa = np.mean(data_CH4[:,[3]])*1e3;            # Atmosphere pressure [Pa]
dp0 = p_CH4[0][0]                             # Initial pressure drop [Pa]

L_CH4 = 2*(pa + 32/3 * (eta/rp) * np.sqrt((2*R*T)/(np.pi * Mw)))  # L Parameter

K_CH4 = L_CH4*10e-11                                              # K Parameter

C_CH4 = np.log(dp0/(dp0 + L_CH4))                                 # C1 Parameter

# Training Data
num_epoch = 1500   # Number of interation
beta = 0.01         # Relaxation factor 
for epoch in range(num_epoch):
    
    # Compute column vector f
    f = fitting_func(L_CH4,K_CH4,C_CH4)
    
    # Calculate the column vector d
    d = p_CH4 - f
    
    # Compute loss
    residue = np.transpose(d).dot(d)[0][0]
    if epoch%100 ==0:
        print(f'Epoch = {epoch+1}/{num_epoch} and residue = {residue}')
    
    # Construct Jacobian matrix
    z1 = dpdL(L_CH4,K_CH4,C_CH4)
    z2 = dpdK(L_CH4,K_CH4,C_CH4)
    z3 = dpdC(L_CH4,K_CH4,C_CH4)
    z = np.hstack([z1,z2,z3])

    # Update the coefficient
    da = np.linalg.inv(np.transpose(z).dot(z)).dot(np.transpose(z).dot(d))
    
    L_CH4 = (L_CH4 + beta*da[0])[0]
    K_CH4 = (K_CH4 + beta*da[1])[0]
    C_CH4 = (C_CH4 + beta*da[2])[0]
